              <h2>How the ocean acidification calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Ocean acidification is driven by the chemistry of the seawater
                carbonate system. This tool focuses on the
                <strong>pH and hydrogen ion concentration</strong> side of the
                story, which is the core of how “acidity” is defined.
              </p>

              <h3>1. From pH to hydrogen ion concentration</h3>
              <p>
                pH is defined as the negative base‑10 logarithm of the hydrogen
                ion activity, which in seawater is usually approximated by
                concentration:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-1">pH = −log<sub>10</sub>[H⁺]</p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">[H⁺] = 10<sup>−pH</sup> (mol/L)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator converts both the reference pH and the
                current/scenario pH into hydrogen ion concentration using this
                relationship.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Acidity increase between two pH values</h3>
              <p>
                Because the pH scale is logarithmic, a small change in pH
                corresponds to a large change in [H⁺]. The ratio of current to
                reference hydrogen ion concentration is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-1">
                  ΔpH = pH<sub>current</sub> − pH<sub>reference</sub>
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-1">
                  Acidity factor = [H⁺]<sub>current</sub> / [H⁺]<sub
                    >reference</sub
                  >
                  = 10<sup>−ΔpH</sup>
                </p>
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  Percent increase in acidity = (Acidity factor − 1) × 100%
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, going from pH 8.20 (pre‑industrial) to pH 8.10
                (modern average) gives:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>ΔpH = −0.10</li>
                <li>Acidity factor = 10<sup>0.10</sup> ≈ 1.26</li>
                <li>Acidity increase ≈ 26%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This is why agencies such as NOAA and the IPCC often state that
                the ocean is now roughly
                <strong>26% more acidic</strong> than it was before large‑scale
                fossil fuel burning.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Illustrative link between CO₂ and pH</h3>
              <p>
                In reality, the relationship between atmospheric CO₂ and ocean
                pH depends on temperature, alkalinity, mixing, and other
                factors. To keep this tool intuitive and fast, we use a
                <strong>simple illustrative model</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm mb-1">
                  pH<sub>approx</sub> = pH<sub>0</sub> − k ·
                  log<sub>10</sub>(CO₂ / CO₂<sub>0</sub>)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">
                  where pH<sub>0</sub> ≈ 8.20 and CO₂<sub>0</sub> = 280 ppm
                  (pre‑industrial), and k is a small constant chosen so that CO₂
                  ≈ 420 ppm gives pH ≈ 8.10.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is <strong>not</strong> a substitute for a full carbonate
                chemistry model, but it visually reinforces the idea that higher
                atmospheric CO₂ is associated with lower ocean pH.
              </p>

              <h2>Why a 0.1 pH drop matters so much</h2>
              <p>
                Many educational resources emphasize that a 0.1–0.3 unit drop in
                ocean pH is a big deal. The calculator makes this concrete by
                showing the underlying [H⁺] change:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>0.1 pH unit drop → ~26% increase in [H⁺]</li>
                <li>0.3 pH unit drop → about 2× increase in [H⁺]</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Marine organisms have evolved in a relatively stable pH
                environment. Rapid changes in [H⁺] can:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Reduce carbonate ion availability, making it harder to build
                  shells and skeletons.
                </li>
                <li>Alter enzyme activity and metabolic processes.</li>
                <li>
                  Change the behavior and survival of larvae and juveniles.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Biological and ecological impacts (high‑level overview)</h2>
              <p>
                While this tool focuses on the chemistry, it is designed to
                complement in‑depth resources from NOAA, EPA, WHOI, and leading
                research institutions. Key impact pathways include:
              </p>
              <h3>Calcifying organisms</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Corals (reef‑building scleractinian corals)</li>
                <li>Mollusks (oysters, clams, mussels, pteropods)</li>
                <li>
                  Some planktonic species (coccolithophores, foraminifera)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Lower pH and carbonate saturation states can slow calcification,
                thin shells, and increase dissolution, threatening reef
                structures and shellfish industries.
              </p>

              <h3>Food webs and fisheries</h3>
              <p>
                Changes at the base of the food web (plankton, pteropods) can
                propagate upward, affecting fish, marine mammals, and human
                communities that depend on fisheries and aquaculture.
              </p>

              <h3>Regional hotspots</h3>
              <p>
                Upwelling regions, polar seas, and coastal zones with strong
                freshwater or nutrient inputs can experience
                <strong>faster and more intense acidification</strong> than the
                global average. Local monitoring and modeling are essential for
                management.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and appropriate use</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is intended for
                <strong
                  >education, outreach, and quick scenario exploration</strong
                >. It does not:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Model full carbonate system speciation (CO₂, HCO₃⁻, CO₃²⁻,
                  borate, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Account for temperature, salinity, alkalinity, or biological
                  feedbacks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Replace professional tools such as CO2SYS, seacarb, or
                  research‑grade models.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For policy, engineering, or research decisions, consult
                peer‑reviewed literature and tools recommended by organizations
                such as NOAA, IPCC, and national oceanographic institutes.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is the ocean already “acidic”?</h3>
              <p>
                Chemically, seawater is still <strong>basic</strong> (pH &gt;
                7). “Ocean acidification” refers to the process of moving toward
                lower pH (more acidic conditions), not that the ocean has
                crossed pH 7. The important point is the
                <strong>change</strong> in pH and [H⁺], not just the absolute
                value.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can local actions help, or is this only a global CO₂ problem?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Reducing global CO₂ emissions is essential, but local actions
                can also help:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Reducing nutrient pollution and organic runoff that drive
                  coastal acidification.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Protecting and restoring seagrasses, mangroves, and wetlands
                  that take up CO₂.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Managing fisheries and aquaculture to increase resilience.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Where can I learn more?</h3>
              <p>
                For deeper dives into the science and impacts of ocean
                acidification, see:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  NOAA Ocean Acidification Program and education resources.
                </li>
                <li>
                  U.S. EPA and European Environment Agency reports on ocean and
                  coastal acidification.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Research institutions such as Woods Hole Oceanographic
                  Institution (WHOI) and AIMS.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
